Perfect üëè ‚Äî that‚Äôs a classic Angular 10 routing linkage issue, and it‚Äôs because your app.config.ts (which you‚Äôre using instead of the usual app.module.ts) is not correctly importing and exporting the routing module.

Let‚Äôs fix this cleanly and clearly üëá

‚∏ª

‚úÖ What‚Äôs happening

You have:
	‚Ä¢	app.routes.ts ‚Äî defines the routes (good ‚úÖ)
	‚Ä¢	app.config.ts ‚Äî supposed to wire everything (like AppModule normally does)

The error:

‚Äúapp.routes declares routes locally but it is not exported‚Äù

means:
Angular can see the routes file, but it‚Äôs not exported as a module for the app to actually use.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ Step-by-step fix

1Ô∏è‚É£ Your app.routes.ts should look exactly like this:

import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { RouterModule, Routes } from '@angular/router';

import { WelcomeComponent } from './welcome/welcome';
import { TravellComponent } from './travell/travell';
import { TravelDetailsComponent } from './travel-details/travel-details';
import { ApprovalsComponent } from './approvals/approvals';

const routes: Routes = [
  { path: '', redirectTo: '/welcome', pathMatch: 'full' },
  { path: 'welcome', component: WelcomeComponent },
  { path: 'new-travel', component: TravellComponent },
  { path: 'travel-details', component: TravelDetailsComponent },
  { path: 'approvals', component: ApprovalsComponent }
];

@NgModule({
  imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes)],
  exports: [RouterModule]  // ‚úÖ this makes it usable by other modules
})
export class AppRoutingModule {}


‚∏ª

2Ô∏è‚É£ Update your app.config.ts

(Think of this as your main Angular module)

Replace it with this:

import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { FormsModule } from '@angular/forms';

import { AppComponent } from './app';
import { TravellComponent } from './travell/travell';
import { TravelDetailsComponent } from './travel-details/travel-details';
import { ApprovalsComponent } from './approvals/approvals';
import { WelcomeComponent } from './welcome/welcome';
import { AppRoutingModule } from './app.routes';  // ‚úÖ import routing module

@NgModule({
  declarations: [
    AppComponent,
    TravellComponent,
    TravelDetailsComponent,
    ApprovalsComponent,
    WelcomeComponent
  ],
  imports: [
    BrowserModule,
    FormsModule,
    AppRoutingModule  // ‚úÖ include router
  ],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent]
})
export class AppModule {}  // ‚úÖ export a proper module


‚∏ª

3Ô∏è‚É£ Update your main.ts

Angular expects to bootstrap the AppModule, not the config file.

So make sure src/main.ts looks like this:

import { platformBrowserDynamic } from '@angular/platform-browser-dynamic';
import { AppModule } from './app/app.config';

platformBrowserDynamic().bootstrapModule(AppModule)
  .catch(err => console.error(err));


‚∏ª

‚úÖ Summary

File	Purpose	Must Export
app.routes.ts	Contains Routes	‚úÖ AppRoutingModule
app.config.ts	Main module	‚úÖ AppModule
main.ts	Bootstraps AppModule	‚úÖ Imports AppModule


‚∏ª

Once you apply these changes, rerun:

ng serve

The error

‚Äúapp.routes declares routes locally but is not exported‚Äù
will disappear üéØ

