Perfect bro üëå those two errors are common TypeScript type-safety issues ‚Äî they‚Äôre happening because:
	1.	In approvals.ts, we‚Äôre passing a number (index) to a function that expects a string parameter.
	2.	In travell.ts, we‚Äôre dynamically assigning object properties using strings, but TypeScript doesn‚Äôt know those property names yet.

Let‚Äôs fix both cleanly and permanently üîß

‚∏ª

‚úÖ 1Ô∏è‚É£ Fix approvals.ts

Here‚Äôs the updated and correct version:

import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';
import { TravelService } from '../services/travel';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-approvals',
  templateUrl: './approvals.html',
  styleUrls: ['./approvals.css']
})
export class ApprovalsComponent implements OnInit {

  travels: any[] = [];

  constructor(private travelService: TravelService) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    this.travels = this.travelService.getTravels();
  }

  updateStatus(index: number, status: string) {
    this.travelService.updateStatus(index, status);
    this.travels = this.travelService.getTravels(); // refresh local copy
  }
}

‚úÖ What changed
	‚Ä¢	The service function updateStatus now explicitly accepts number instead of string.
	‚Ä¢	We refresh the local travels list after updating the status, so UI updates immediately.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ 2Ô∏è‚É£ Fix in travel.service.ts

Let‚Äôs make sure this service handles the update properly:

import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class TravelService {

  private travels: any[] = [];

  addTravel(travel: any) {
    this.travels.push({ ...travel, status: 'Approval Pending' });
  }

  getTravels() {
    return this.travels;
  }

  updateStatus(index: number, status: string) {
    if (this.travels[index]) {
      this.travels[index].status = status;
    }
  }
}

‚úÖ What changed
	‚Ä¢	updateStatus() now takes index: number, no more type mismatch.
	‚Ä¢	Safe check added to prevent undefined errors.

‚∏ª

‚úÖ 3Ô∏è‚É£ Fix travell.ts (form component)

You likely have something like:

this.travel[fieldName] = value;

TypeScript complains because it doesn‚Äôt know your object‚Äôs shape.
Fix it like this:

interface TravelForm {
  uid: string;
  name: string;
  lineManager: string;
  domain: string;
  cluster: string;
  subCluster: string;
  cluster1: string;
  hod: string;
  travelType: string;
  originCity: string;
  destinationCity: string;
  startDate: string;
  endDate: string;
  travelClass: string;
  type: string;
  purpose: string;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-travell',
  templateUrl: './travell.html',
  styleUrls: ['./travell.css']
})
export class TravellComponent {
  travel: TravelForm = {
    uid: '',
    name: '',
    lineManager: '',
    domain: '',
    cluster: '',
    subCluster: '',
    cluster1: '',
    hod: '',
    travelType: '',
    originCity: '',
    destinationCity: '',
    startDate: '',
    endDate: '',
    travelClass: '',
    type: '',
    purpose: ''
  };

  constructor(private travelService: TravelService) {}

  onSubmit() {
    this.travelService.addTravel(this.travel);
    alert('Travel request submitted successfully!');
  }
}

‚úÖ Why this works
	‚Ä¢	The TravelForm interface defines the expected fields ‚Äî no more dynamic ‚Äú${string}s‚Äù issues.
	‚Ä¢	TypeScript now knows the exact shape of travel.

